article.description: After struggling most of the game, Ezra Williams hit three straight 3-pointers in the closing minutes to lead Georgia (No. 17 ESPN/USA Today, No. 15 AP) to a 67-63 victory over Mississippi State (No. 22 ESPN/USA Today, No. 21 AP) on Saturday night.
article.headline: Williams lifts Georgia over Mississippi State
article.linkText: Williams heats up at right time for Georgia
article.story: ATHENS, Ga. (AP) -- The ball wasn't dropping, but Ezra Williams kept right on shooting. Good thing for Georgia. After struggling most of the game, Williams hit three straight 3-pointers in the closing minutes to lead (No. 17 ESPN/USA Today, No. 15 AP) Georgia to a 67-63 victory over (No. 22 ESPN/USA Today, No. 21 AP) Mississippi State on Saturday night. "I just had to turn it up,'' said Williams, who finished with 17 points after starting 2-of-12 from the field. "I'm a shooter. That stuff happens. I still have confidence in myself.'' Steve Thomas and Chris Daniels carried Georgia (13-5, 5-2 Southeastern Conference) until Williams took over at the end. Mississippi State (13-5, 3-4) led 59-54 after Winsome Frazier hit a towering, off-balance trey with 3:50 remaining. Timmy Bowers probably could have clinched it on State's next possession, but he put up an airball from the corner with Daniels in his face. That gave Georgia its chance. Williams, disregarding his ugly shooting line, swished a shot from well outside the arc to boost his confidence. Derrick Zimmerman missed a driving shot, and Williams sank another 3 to give Georgia a 60-59 lead with 1:50 to go. After Zimmerman missed again, Jarvis Hayes rimmed out a 3-pointer for Georgia. But Daniels scrambled for the offensive rebound and found Williams lurking at the arc. With a clear look at the basket, he sank his third straight 3 with 54 seconds remaining to essentially clinch the victory. "On a night when we couldn't throw one in the ocean, to win this way is very, very gratifying,'' coach Jim Harrick said. "I haven't seen a team of mine shoot like that in a long, long time.'' The 3-pointer was certainly an unlikely weapon for Georgia, which shot only 5-of-24 outside the arc. State wasn't much better, going 5-of-21. "Ezra did just what he does to everybody,'' State coach Rick Stansbury said. "I thought we did a tremendous job on him. It was just the timely shots he made.'' Without Daniels and Thomas, Georgia wouldn't have had a chance to win at the end. Hayes had a miserable game, shooting just 2-of-12 for five points, his lowest total in two seasons with the Bulldogs. Daniels scored a season-high 16 points, only the second time in six games he's been in double figures. He also led the team with nine rebounds and chipped in with two steals, two blocks and two assists. Thomas had 13 points, eight rebounds, three blocks, two assists and a steal. Daniels admitted he might have gotten away with a foul on the key defensive stop against Bowers, running straight at the shooter. "I knew the play was going to go to him and I cheated my way out there,'' Daniels said. Daniels and Thomas also did good work on Mario Austin, holding State's leading scorer to 14 points. "Chris and Steve carried us in the first half,'' Williams said. "They did a tremendous job on Mario. Then Mississippi State slowed it down.'' State switched to a zone to get back in the game. Georgia went nearly five minutes without scoring, allowing State to grab a 52-49 lead. Williams, who hadn't made a 3 all game, finally hit from long range to break the drought with 7:56 remaining and tie it at 52. Bowers added 13 points for Mississippi State, which had a three-game winning streak snapped. Georgia bounced back from a 94-91 loss at Vanderbilt on Wednesday. Hayes has struggled since injuring his hip in a Jan. 22 victory over Tennessee. He is just 11-of-38 from the field in the last three games. "It's kind of frustrating to watch Jarvis,'' Williams said. "We just need to get him healthy. This team needs him.'' Even Hayes came up with a big play at the end. With Georgia clinging to a 65-61 lead, Bowers got loose under the basket off an inbounds pass. Hayes came out of nowhere to flick the shot away while State's bench screamed futilely for a goaltending call. Georgia held the upper hand most of the first half, reeling off a 12-2 spurt after Austin's basket with 14:10 left gave Mississippi State a 9-8 lead. Georgia came up with another run at the end of the half, outscoring State 12-4 to go up 40-29 at the break. Thomas accounted for six of the points, Daniels four.
